Dataset Summary

## [1] 113937     81

There are 113,937 loans with 81 variables.

## [1] "2005-11-09 20:44:28.847000000" "2014-03-10 12:20:53.760000000"

We can see the first loan in the dataset originated on 2015-11-09 and the latest loan we have in the dataset is from 2014-03-10.

The dataset I will be exploring is loan data from Prosper, a peer-to-peer lending platform. Borrowers can borrow up to $2,000 to $35,000 from the marketplace and lenders can base their decision on the borrowers credit history and loan information.

I will being my analysis with a short summary of the data and then I will create univariate plots to understand the structure of individual variables I am interested in learning more about.

The Prosper Score risk rankings looks normally distriuted with the mean close to 6.

I noticed 29,084 rows of data consisted of NA. After looking further into it, I noticed it these loans originated before before July 2009. Loans that originated before July 2009 do not have data for ProsperScore, ProsperRating (alpha), ProsperRating (numeric), EstimatedReturn, EstimatedEffectiveYield, and EstimatedLoss.

Since the company was founded in 2005 to Q2 of 2008, the company saw a steady increase in the number of loans originated. But as most of the developed world dove deep into the recession, the number of loan originations decreased significantly untl there were no loans originating in Q1 2009.

What is the structure of your dataset?

The structure of the dataset consists of 81 variables with 113937 observations. Each observation is a loan and the variables describe the loans with details of the loan and details of the borrower. The observations are from 2005 to 2014. The variable types are int, num, and ch.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest in the dataset are the yield and return rates along with the various amount of loan characteristics. This will allow me to guess what are the common loan characteristics of loans that become delinquent and what loans characteristics makes the loan a safe investment.

Another feature which interested me what how I can view through plots the effects of the recession on the loan market

Bivariate Plots Section

## Warning: Removed 7604 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

For this plot, I was expecting the borrower rate to increase as bank card utilization increased because a high bank card utilization rate may indicate that the borrower is not able to pay off their credit card frequently and thus has to pay the high interest rates on credit cards.

And we can see this trend in the plot after adjusting the alpha. As the borrower rate increases, so does the bank card utilization. In the area where the borrower rate is high and the bank card utilizaton is low, we can see there are not many loans. An interesting feature of this plot is that as bank card utilization increases, the borrower rate becomes more dispersed. It looks like a skewed-funnel.

Maybe there are relationships between the utilization rate and other variables that are in play here as the utilization rate increases.

Another interesting feature of this plot is that at the 100% utilization rate there seems to be a limit, however there are a small amount of loans above the 100% utilization rate. This could be because of the new credit requirements that banks and landers had to follow which the government introduced after the recession or maybe it could be that once borowers hit 100% of their card utilization, they looked elsewhere for credit.

We can see that the limit at 100% utilization in the post recession plot a more defined than the pre recession plot. There are many more loans that have > 100% card utilizaion pre recession than post recession, this could be due to more stringent borrowing requirements enacted by Prosper after the recession.

Let’s conduct a correlation test to measure the strength of this relationship.

cor.test(pld$BankcardUtilization, pld$BorrowerRate, method = "pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  pld$BankcardUtilization and pld$BorrowerRate
## t = 86.168, df = 106330, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2498551 0.2610917
## sample estimates:
##      cor 
## 0.255482

With a p-value of 2.2e-16, this is much less than the significance level of alpha = 0.05. We can conclude that bank card utilization and borrower rate are significantly correlated.

Let’s continue investigating what effects the borrower rate.

We can see that most of the loans with borrowers that have a high amount of available credit have a lower borrower rate as expected.

The two variables have a positive relationship at a debt to income of approximately 0.4, then seems to fall and rise where there are not a great number of loans.

There seems to be a negative relationship between the two variables. For the credit scores over 750, the borrower rate is low and the ranges of borrowing rates is smaller for most of the loans compared to borrowing rates for borrowers with lower credits scores.

Let’s compare the borrower rate with the prosper score to see if there is a stronger relationship.

As we can see, the higher the prosper score for a loan, the lower the borrowing rate is.

But how accurate are prosper scores in determining if a loan will perform or not?

Prosper scores 5-11 follow the pattern I was expecting. I am surprised by the difference in the default rates from prosper score 1 to score 2. And it’s surprising that prosper scores 2-4 have a similar performance of loans with scores of 6-8.

Another interesting observation is the large amount of defaults for loans originated before before July 2009.

Let’s take a look into the return rates for borrowers for each quarter. Based on this plot, I expect return rates to be much lower before July 2009 than return rates after July 2009.

We have to keep in mind that the plot graphs the estimated lender yield as it is calculated at the origination of the loan. Lender yield rose until Q4 2010 and started falling.

Next I will calculate the actual return on a loan by subracting losses(if any) from the original loan amount and will annulize the return.

By the calculations, Prosper lenders experienced losses from Prosper’s inception and through the recession and provided positive returns after prosper was required to register with the SEC. Q2 2009 was quite interesting as all loans received $0 in customer payments, therefore it was removed from the plot to make it more readable.

For loans that have existed for less than 12 months and are in good standing their returns were annualized.

We can see for most loans that the actual return was lower than the predicted lender yield. We can also see the change in distribution between the two plots before and after the recession; loans that experienced losses realized greater losses before the recession than after.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plots the relationship between the estimated lender yield, debt to income and the Prosper score. In the bottom left corner where debt to income is low, the Prosper score is higher and intuitively, the lender yield is low. But as the lender yield increases, so does the Prosper score and debt to income. However, there are still borrowers with low debt to income and a high lender, this could be due to other factors that make the borrower more risky.

Plot Two

## Warning: Removed 29084 rows containing non-finite values (stat_count).

Description Two

This plot shows how the relationship between the Prosper score and actual yield. At the lower end Prosper scores, these loans are deemed very risky, you can expect a yield anywhere between a great loss or a great positive yield. And this is apparent in the proportion of the return buckets for each Prosper score. The saying “the greater the risk the greater the return… or loss” is visible here. At the higher end of the Prosper scores, these loans are very safe and are the least likely to default, hence their returns are low. The patterns of the proportions are just as I would expect the to be as the Prosper score changes. As the Prosper score goes higher, the proportions of loans with very high loans decreases along wih the proportion of loans with very low returns.

Plot Three

Description Three

For the third graph, I decided to keep it simple and plotted the actual yield vs the estimated yield. This is to show the great difference between them two. I’m sure all of the lenders that experienced losses with Prosper would be very frsustrated at seeing these results as it’s apparent that Prosper didn’t do their due diligence in screening their borrowers until they were forced to register with the SEC.

Reflection

This dataset was very interesting to analyze. There were some variables that I expected to have a strong relationship to the estimated yield, but didin’t. This made me realize that there are many other variables to consider when determining the risk of an individual borrower. However, I did expect to see a stronger relationship between the credit card utilization and the borrower rate as credit card utilization, to me, determines if a borrower understand how inefficient it is to borrow money from a credit card as they have very high interest rates. If a borrower has high credit card utilization then I’d deem them to be a risky borrower as they don’t seem to understand what should be their financial priorities.

This project made me a lot more comfortable with using R as it forced me to manipulate the data, create different types of plots, create new variables to see new insights, and to choose the best way to visualize the data. I struggles with some of the data manipulation, but searching the web made it a lot easier to solve as many other people have documented similar struggles along with their solutions.

If I had more time with the dataset, I would have tried to create a model that mimics the way the Prosper score is calculated.
